@flexiarg math-strategy/compose-independent-lemmas
@title Compose Independent Lemmas
@sigils [🧩/合]
@keywords compose, assemble, combine, independent, lemma, modular, convergent, conclusion
@audience mathematicians, proof-writers
@tone heuristic
@factor Concentration (samādhi)

! conclusion:
  When a proof requires multiple independent pieces, establish each piece
  separately and then compose them in a final step that adds nothing new.

  + context: Your main result follows from several sub-results that can be
    proved independently. The conclusion is a logical composition (conjunction,
    chain of implications, or substitution) of the pieces.

  + IF:
      The sub-results address different concerns (existence, uniqueness,
      nontriviality, notation compatibility, etc.) and no sub-result's proof
      depends on another sub-result being true.

  + HOWEVER:
      Independence must be genuine, not assumed. If lemma B uses lemma A as
      a hypothesis, they are not independent — B depends on A. The composition
      step must also be checked: it is tempting to wave hands at "combining"
      results when the combination itself requires a non-trivial argument
      (e.g., that two constructions refer to the same object, or that
      hypotheses of one result are satisfied by another).

  + THEN:
      (a) Identify the independent pieces. Draw the dependency graph.
      (b) For each piece, verify it is self-contained: its proof uses only its
          own hypotheses and prior results, not sibling lemmas.
      (c) Write the composition step as a separate, explicit argument. It
          should be short — if it is long, one of the pieces is incomplete.
      (d) Check that the composition step does not silently introduce new
          claims. Every assertion in the composition must trace to a piece.

  + BECAUSE:
      Modular proofs are easier to review, easier to repair, and easier to
      generalize. When a reviewer finds a gap, modular structure localizes
      the damage: you know which piece is broken and which are unaffected.
      A monolithic proof hides dependencies and makes gaps contagious.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[List the pieces and draw the dependency graph.]
    next[Verify each piece is self-contained.]
    next[Write the composition step. Keep it short.]
    next[Trace every assertion in the composition to its source piece.]
